		   <table class="mform2"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Sat, Oct 23rd 10:45 PM2004 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/db/classes.html?class=2&mid=1098533899740644821&num=5&post=1&replyto=1098585992194361889"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1098585992194361889></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=427265"><span id=Scholar>RattailScoundral</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br />42 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=RattailScoundral&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p> Rogues are perhaps the most enjoyable of the pure melee classes because they have the most diversity and flexibility. Those of a narrower vision or d00ds who focus only on melee ability are not dissapointed as rogues dish out enormous damage-per-second, even from the front (althought their forte is obviously the back). <br><br> However, they are much more than just a fighter, Rogues have plenty of skills that give flavor to the raw damage-output class they are. Most notibly is their ability to invis themself, dont think I have to explain the uses of that. Their ability to pick pockets gives them something fun to do between backstabs and disarms, lining their pocket with decent coin and even items. Their ability to sense and disarm traps makes them a welcome utility in dungeons, as is their ability to pick locks. Their make poison skills adds a devilish grin to the fun, giving way to the assassin aspect of being a rogue and can tip the balance for the spell-deprived.<br><br> They make excellant scouts and are a blast if you're a roleplayer. If straight hunting and raiding is your only interest, rogues are hard to beat for DPS. I have never played a warrior, so I cant compare the two defensively, but I do know that rogues get enough defensive skills matched with their usually high AGI that they can even tank if the need calls until the end game.<br><br> My rogue is currently level 40 and can still solo unbuffed. While it's not the best way for a rogue to get XP, solo ability is important to me for killing nameds and quest mobs when I have nobody around to help me. His high defensive ability allows him to weave between attacks and take minimal damage during fights while his enormous damage rate brings the mob down quickly.<br><br> Vah Shir have great stats for a rogue, a high agility without depriving their STR and STA. However, they would not be my first choice. Their racial abilities (Sneak and Safe Fall) are made obsolete by the class abilities and I personally shudder at the thought of a large race being a rogue.&nbsp;&nbsp;If you're a roleplayer, note that Vah Shir rogues (Taruun) are considered to be hunter-scouts more than thief-assassins, close to home with being a ranger in RP.<br><br> Never have I had more fun than the rogue, in 2 years of Everquest. I would have never expected a class without spells would be any fun, I'd reccomend rogue to just about anyone at least to try. Good luck and have fun.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from a computer</td><td align="right" id="fs8" >0 Replies</td></tr></table>
</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td>

